hands_on_practices.solution:
A counter-clockwise Givens rotation in 2D with cosine $c$ and sine $s$ is represented by the matrix
$$
R(c,s)=\begin{pmatrix} c & -s \\ s & c \end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying the first rotation with $c_{1}=\frac{12}{13}$ and $s_{1}=\frac{5}{13}$ to $v_{0}=\begin{pmatrix}13\\26\end{pmatrix}$ gives
$$
v_{1}=R(c_{1},s_{1})\,v_{0}
=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{12}{13} & -\frac{5}{13} \\ \frac{5}{13} & \frac{12}{13} \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}13\\26\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{12}{13}\cdot 13-\frac{5}{13}\cdot 26 \\ \frac{5}{13}\cdot 13+\frac{12}{13}\cdot 26 \end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} 12-10 \\ 5+24 \end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 29 \end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying the second rotation with $c_{2}=\frac{3}{5}$ and $s_{2}=\frac{4}{5}$ to $v_{1}$ yields
$$
v_{2}=R(c_{2},s_{2})\,v_{1}
=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{3}{5} & -\frac{4}{5} \\ \frac{4}{5} & \frac{3}{5} \end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}2\\29\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{3}{5}\cdot 2-\frac{4}{5}\cdot 29 \\ \frac{4}{5}\cdot 2+\frac{3}{5}\cdot 29 \end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} \frac{6-116}{5} \\ \frac{8+87}{5} \end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix} -22 \\ 19 \end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus the final coordinates as a row matrix are $[-22 \ 19]$. As a check, the Euclidean norm is preserved: $\|v_{0}\|^{2}=13^{2}+26^{2}=845$ and $\|v_{2}\|^{2}=(-22)^{2}+19^{2}=845$.

Let $r=\sqrt{b^{2}+c^{2}}$. Since $b^{2}+c^{2}\neq 0$, we have $r>0$.

First Givens rotation $G_{1}$ acts on the $(y,z)$-plane (indices $2,3$) and is chosen so that it maps $[b,c]^{T}$ to $[r,0]^{T}$. Using the standard Givens construction to zero out the third component, we must use a rotation that maps $[b, c]^T$ to $[r, 0]^T$. The rotation matrix that does this is $G_{23}(\theta_1) = \begin{pmatrix} \cos\theta_1 & \sin\theta_1 \\ -\sin\theta_1 & \cos\theta_1 \end{pmatrix}$ with $\cos\theta_1 = b/r$ and $\sin\theta_1 = c/r$. The problem defines $G_{ij} = -\sin\theta$ and $G_{ji}=\sin\theta$, which is the counter-clockwise rotation matrix $\begin{pmatrix} \cos\theta & -\sin\theta \\ \sin\theta & \cos\theta \end{pmatrix}$. To make the second entry of the result zero (i.e., mapping $[b, c]^T \to [r, 0]^T$), we need $\sin\theta_1 b + \cos\theta_1 c = 0$. So we choose $\cos\theta_{1}=\frac{b}{r}$ and $\sin\theta_{1}=-\frac{c}{r}$.
Thus
$$
G_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{b}{r} & \frac{c}{r}\\
0 & -\frac{c}{r} & \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying this to $\mathbf{v}$ gives
$$
\mathbf{v}' = G_{1}\mathbf{v}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{b}{r} & \frac{c}{r}\\
0 & -\frac{c}{r} & \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}a\\ b\\ c\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\
\frac{b^{2}+c^{2}}{r}\\
\frac{-cb+bc}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ r\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}.
$$

Second Givens rotation $G_{2}$ acts on the $(x,y)$-plane (indices $1,2$) and is chosen so that it maps $[a,r]^{T}$ to $[1,0]^{T}$. Since $a^{2}+r^{2}=1$, we set
$\cos\theta_{2}=a$ and $\sin\theta_{2}=-r$. This gives
$$
G_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}
a & r & 0\\
-r & a & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Applying this to $\mathbf{v}'$ gives
$$
G_{2}\mathbf{v}'=
\begin{pmatrix}
a & r & 0\\
-r & a & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ r\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a^2+r^2\\ -ra+ar\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1\\ 0\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
=\mathbf{e}_{1}.
$$

Therefore, the composite rotation is $R=G_{2}G_{1}$. Multiplying,
$$
R
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a & r & 0\\
-r & a & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \frac{b}{r} & \frac{c}{r}\\
0 & -\frac{c}{r} & \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a & b & c\\
-r & \frac{ab}{r} & \frac{ac}{r}\\
0 & -\frac{c}{r} & \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
A direct check shows $R\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{e}_{1}$ since
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
a & b & c\\
-r & \frac{ab}{r} & \frac{ac}{r}\\
0 & -\frac{c}{r} & \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ b\\ c
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\\
-ar+\frac{a(b^{2}+c^{2})}{r}\\
\frac{-cb+bc}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus, with $r=\sqrt{b^{2}+c^{2}}$, the desired composite rotation matrix is as above.
